To my left this afternoon, I have a panel of individuals who each represent an aspect of this equation.

and a distinguished collector whose own collection he's making available slowly but surely through Octavo Books.

Even better, when I got out of college from September of 71 to September of 72, having a main position really as an acting rare book librarian during a hiatus between two professional appointments,

um this is just wonderful it gave me a chance to learn about a hobby get paid for doing it getting to know a collection a collection in a very tactile intimate way there's a time when i could point out identify immediately every location of every rare book on the shelves you can do that if you have 25 or 30 40 000 titles uh reflections bigger today and i couldn't do it but it was really one of the great formative experiences of my life and
As a result of that, I have tried to support the library primarily through donations over a period now that would extend at least over 30 years.

Charles Van Riemen's way, who were directors of the museum.
And these are people you don't forget.
And my own collecting interest, as Mark said, initially began to be focused on architecture and ornament and decoration with a little more of a continental orientation.
But what I've tried to do is to give the library gifts that really complement the collections they have.

uh in many cases these are not high spot books because um the library was buying in the early 50s from people like bassford where you could walk and just sweep the shelves there for the second world war before these pattern books became fashionable and so they have they have robert adams with contemporary coloring and they have you know the uh hamilton studies and things of this kind but um

These are the kind of things that are filled there.

You know exactly who's going to be using the material.
There are no questions about hypothetical issues, but will it be appreciated?
Will it be used?
And there's also a very, very important conservation laboratory effort and post-master's degree program associated with winter tours.

I don't think that this material is, it's not impossibly scarce.
I've never, I've never
at any sort of period of time when there hasn't been more available than I can possibly afford to buy.
And I don't really see that changing.
I think the only area that really is becoming very difficult now is fine 16th century continental ornament, even more so than architectural books.
And that's really because so much of this has gotten in the hands of the print dealers.

And I hope there are no print dealers here, but they are the absolute antagonist of book collectors because when you start selling things by the page and pricing them like old by the sheet and pricing them like old master prints, you completely lose the frame of reference that most book collectors are constantly dealing in.
But there's at least one very important collection in this field that will come onto the market in the next five years.
So there will be opportunities to fill any gaps in that area.
The institution's role, I mean, I think in the case of Winter Tour, has been, as I said, being exemplary, and I think it's a model for what you would want to do.
I mean, you know, I had, even as a non-employee, I had access to the stack on a control base.
There was mentorship, there were
librarians who were collectors themselves.

They made introductions to me as a very young person with really no money to some of the prominent dealers on the continent and in England and in the United States, which enabled me to jumpstart my own activities probably by about 10 years.

The emphasized bibliography, I mean, no one gave me a set of standard bibliographies in my field, but I was told early on that I needed the Burlady catalog, I needed the full sale, I needed two or three other important catalogs, which I bought, and it's amazing what you can learn by reading bibliographies, and that's an interest that I've picked up in only in the last four or five years.

I think these models can work, and I've had some other relationships, the Press Library at Harvard's own involving one, and certainly the Houghton Library has been very rewarding in certain contexts, but I think the Winter Tour one is unique in my experience, but I think it's a model that particularly the smaller and highly focused library can probably develop, and I think it pays to cultivate
sort of identify your targets if you are a librarian, identify your candidates early on.
And I actually, the first time I met Bill Reese was in the fall of 1971.
And Bill didn't even have a driver's license.
And then he was a very nice parent and very nice sister.
And Bill was looking at the Audubon and the rest is history.
So thank you all for the chance.

Well, one of the reasons that I enjoy coming to programs like this is that it reminds one of the reasons that librarians do what they do and gives someone like myself a few moments to reflect back on how I feel about what we do and how we contribute to scholarships.
On the wall outside my office, I have a
list of the librarians at Brown University going back to the 1760s.
One of whom I might add was a gentleman by the name of Increase Sumner Smith.
That is an appropriate name for a librarian.
I don't know what is.
But I keep it there for two reasons.
One, of course, is to remind people who come into the office that
The position I hold is an old and distinguished one, and distinguished for good reason.
That is because it's important to the institution.
But also to remind myself that, and hopefully the folks who work in the library, that that library was there many years before we came.
It's the product of the hard work, not only of our predecessors, but of the passion and the devotion of collectors
such as we have here today, and we have it in our hands for really a fleeting moment in the history of that institution.
And it's our role, and it's certainly, I feel, my role to try to pass it on to those who come after us, hopefully in better shape than where I found it.
in every respect.
And it's not simply a position, it's an inheritance.
And it's something for us to lead through the future.

And I think when you talk about the role of special collections and research libraries, I think one of the things that we have to offer to collectors and where there's a real connection is that kind of shared passion
and commitment to the future of a vision that we're building on parents' paths and moving that forward for the generations long after us will benefit by it.
It's a more lasting way of keeping someone's work alive, I think, often than a building.
As someone who works often with donors,
or hear stories about donors to the university, there's great excitement often about having your name on a building.
But I think those of us who work in institutions and particularly old ones have also seen the buildings that are torn down or the buildings that change their name down the line.

And for that reason, I think I often say an endowment for books is a much longer lasting memorial in some cases to someone, certainly a collection that is given to an institution and will be built upon and used for many future generations as a great living legacy.
On my own role in all of this, I'm very honored to have Mark
sort of adopt me as a member of the rare book community.
This is a community with excessively high standards and the one which many library directors probably can't need.
But I think my role more than anything else is to find the resources and provide support.
So that the Special Collections people at Brown who have the knowledge of this field and the content expertise can go and do what they do and work with the donors.
My goal is to help to reassure the donors that if a collection comes to our institution, it will be cherished and taken care of and preserved.

And I think part of the role, and as mentioned earlier today, but perhaps not at great length, I think it's hard to underestimate the complexity today of the competition within institutions of higher education for funds.
And I mean, not only for the library to get funds when you are looking, for example, at pressure to compete in financial aid,
or at our institution providing support for graduate research, graduate fellowship.
All of these things are things where the library is competing on institutional levels of resources.
And then within the library, there is intense composition for the existing class.
And I think one of the things the director is always in the position of balancing is
how much of the available funds go to Special Collections versus the digital and versus other projects that are greatly cherished.

So I always urge when I'm talking to audiences where there are many people from Special Collections to put the time in to educate the library director as much as you can because there's someone for whom there's a great deal of competition for the support.
I want to agree with the comments that's been made by several people that I don't believe that the possibilities for collecting are drying up.
Scholarship is voracious.
It's moving into areas that when I was an undergraduate, no one would have believed that certain things would become for academic attention.
But to give you an example,
Not long ago, we were given a collection, and we're happy to be given a collection, of 60,000 comic books.
Now, the thing that amazed me about this was the press this got, because the carrying on in the press was much along the lines of, Ivy League University Library collects comic books.
What has the world come to?
Or this is quite an external thing.
Whereas I think we felt that comic books, aside from being an art form, are increasingly becoming important cultural studies.
They're increasingly being produced as serious works of literature, although they're illustrated.
And furthermore, and this is always an important issue for an academic institution, this collection fit in beautifully with other materials in our collection.
So we didn't consider it to be odd at all.
And neither is the gentleman who had built this fine collection and is still building it.
So I think where there is a variety of human interest, there is always going to be a variety of collecting.
And there's, at least I am not concerned about one day folks putting out things to collect and hopefully give to us.
In 1982, my partner and I, Chuck Yushke and I, founded Adobe Systems.
And when we founded Adobe, we had no concept that the company for the last 18 years would completely change the world of printing and publishing.
Almost every magazine, newspaper, book in the world today of modern presses
uses our technology, so our interest in the history of type and the interest of the history of printing has been always sort of part of the fabric of our professional life.
How I got into collecting, this is a funny story.
Our family was at the Grosvenor Housing and Teak Fair in 1987, and we were going back to buy the Nags food stall.
And my son came up to me and he said, Dad, look at this.
And there was this big book, and I pulled it off the shelf.
And it was a 1570 copy of Euclid's Elements that was first edition in English.
And if you open this book, it had these wonderful little pop-up figures of all the geometry of Euclid.
While I studied at its philosophy in college,
I said, oh my god.
I really never had realized that such books even existed, much less that you could buy them.
And so I looked at the price, and since Adobe had just gone public, I decided, well, this is nifty.
I really have to have this book.
So I took the book home.
and put it up on the shelf, and that was a mistake because if you put it up on the shelf, there it is, all by itself.
And you say to yourself, this book means friends.
And that starts this ongoing and all-consuming disease that lasts over many, many years because you find more and more friends to add to the community of books.
I would characterize my collection as a high point collection in science and mathematics and philosophy and economics.
And there aren't many books, but they're good books.
The other thing that occurred to me is when I started giving talks on these books, I used to take a couple of the books to go with the talks.
We talked about books without the books are sort of boring.
But when people see these first editions of Newton and Galileo, all of this emotion comes out of it.
I mean, my God, these are real seminal events in the history of mankind.
And so then I thought to myself, gee, wouldn't it be great if every high school kid could have access to all of this stuff?
and yet at the same time not destroy them in the process.

And so I mowed this around with a friend at work, and we decided to start Octavo with the express purpose of using the technology to photograph every page of the book and put them in electronic form and make them available in a very unknown price.
And so the disposition of my collection, the best disposition would be if all of my collection was available to everybody for a very nominal price.
The artifacts, as I completely agree with Bill Ries, they're icons.
There will be nothing like holding one of these things in your hand and knowing that you've got a piece of history.
But not everybody can do that.
And even special collections and libraries can't do that because they can't let everybody in.
It destroys the book over time.

But we're working very closely with the Folger Museum and the Library of Congress and Mark and Daniel have been great supporters and Richard from the Folger have been great supporters of trying to get these things in individual forms so that everybody can look at the type, look at the paper texture,
and get to look and feel with the folks.
Because I think the final outcome should be, all of these things should be made ultimately accessible.
So that's my goal of life.
And that's what the collection is all about.
Thanks very much.
Let's try getting to the, I think, the common thread of this morning.
We've heard it in a variety of ways.
I know it's certainly the topic that a lot of people are talking about after this morning.
Is it fair to say that when we look at collectors and librarians and the dealers who are often either the agents between us or for us, that we're at odds with each other?
This morning we heard various phrases that either suggested that collectors are no longer collecting what libraries need, that there are consistently mentioned or issues of trust,
a sense of security for the part of the collector, a sense of fear that their books would be abandoned.
We heard about the magnetic force of gifts to libraries and what they can do.
It's understood that we all share a spirit or a passion for book materials.
We've all been striving for the word today, Hindi, I think works pretty well.
But beyond that, are we at a point where collectors and librarians are describing a different passion?
It was suggested this morning that there's a difference between caretaking and stewardship, and is this the point in which collectors and librarians differ?
This comes from the spirit, certainly, of the librarian in which we would like collections to come to us, however that, whatever path that might be.
So, I'll throw that out and see if people have some response to it.
I guess, again, one speaks from one's experience.
It's been a pretty symbiotic and fairly happy trinity for me.
Again, as I said, I know where my books are going, and I'm not trying to make converts.
I'm trying to help build a collection or two that's already existing.
highly regarded in an area that is complementary to one that I am in.

libraries are cutting edge in terms of curatorial services and conservation.

And certainly the booksellers are, I agree with people who said that the booksellers are really the lubrication for a lot of what we do.
I don't know many other collectors in my field, and there may be some.
I'm sure there are a few of them around.
But dealers are really the ultimate of open-stacked libraries.
I mean, everything is for sale.
Almost everything is for sale.
And they let you come in, and they let you hold things.
And books are very tactile, particularly if you're interested in illustrated books and buying things, as I am.
So that works pretty well.
And some libraries, I think,
Some libraries, particularly large ones, do continue to be intimidating to someone on the outside and it takes a lot of time to penetrate physically into the libraries.

I think that the dealer and collector relationship is essential.
You build a strong bond of trust to the dealer.
They know your taste and what kind of books you'll consider and what kind of books you won't consider.
For the most part, and you find out about the other ones, for the most part they're very, very ethical.
I've run across a couple that aren't, but that's rare, I think.
They have incredible knowledge, as you say, to seeing dozens of copies of books, and they try to represent the books fairly.
So I've used probably a dozen readers all over the world that I trust with, and they are the source.
I mean, they are the ones who rooted out auction houses lessons.
My own personal contact tends to be more with collectors than it does with dealers, but I would say that in the institutions I've worked in,
the relationship between libraries, dealers, and collectors has been overwhelmingly positive.
And dealers have been very helpful to the library in a number of ways.
And certainly, we at Brown have a number of long-term and very interested and involved collectors with whom we work.
Sometimes there can be frustrations on both sides.
I read an article some years ago, and I'm ashamed to say I cannot remember the author at this point, but essentially it was called bereavement and the collector.
And it made the analogy that when a collector makes a decision to sell or give a collection to an institution,
The collector often goes through the same stages of grief as you do when you lose someone who's very dear to you.
You have anger, grief, denial.
I don't remember all those things.
I think perhaps the more appropriate analogy is giving away your child in marriage.
You still have a decent investment.
this entity would not exist, it hasn't been for your position and hard work, but now you've got to sort of let go and let .
And I think it's important, communication is a very important part of it.
It's very important for institutions to make sure that the collector knows from the beginning that the institution may not have
exactly the same aims for that collection as the collector did.

In other words, if your collection is going to the institution of higher education, there's an interest in that institution in having a collection of scholarship and that the collection relates to materials you already have.
You may not develop the collection in the exact same way that the collector would have and he or she kept it under this control.
The more these things are discussed openly and comfortably, then I think the less you understand the frustration you have down the line.
The other thing I often think collectors may experience for the first time in working with an institution who has assigned their collection is the awesome ability to drive both parties to deal crazy.
From the point of view of the library, as I often tell our staff, the library does not exist alone as part of a larger bureaucracy.
It means that such issues as getting checks cut or getting papers signed in a seamless and smooth way that you might have with a transaction between two individuals.
We do the best we can to
make this easy for the collectors and the donors, but there are some types of pitches along the way.
In a general sense, I think of dealers as being colleagues of mine.
I'm not sure all dealers feel that same way about auction houses.
But I certainly think that dealers play a greater role in nurturing private collectors.
than an auction house can.
By the nature of our business, we're much more concerned, frankly, with sellers than with buyers.
We figure if we have something like a receiver in the library to sell, the buyers are going to come to it.
So it's hard for us sometimes to get to know collectors

in the same way as dealers do i think still this sense of intimidation about attending an auction i think occasionally dealers like to play up that presumption to keep private bidders out of the rooms

By anyone other than Dr. Siebert himself.
with the assumption that collections lead a life that ultimately end up in a library.

That's from a purely personal point of view.
I think this has been very much what I was saying before about two things that are struggling today in the conversation.

Bob Jackson's point about the need for libraries to reach out to collectors who may not know that we have an interest in what they're doing, particularly, again, if they're collecting in areas that they may not see as some serious scholarship or a serious interest in higher education.
But having the words done that, then I think having a discussion about why

you believe the collection belongs to the institution, what you will do with it, how you will, and I know this is not a popular word in our community, but I'll use it anyway, market the collection so that
There's a wide knowledge.

One of the things I think that has made a great difference in the use of special collections over the last 20 years has been the retrospective cataloging projects where there was a time when in order to use certain collections, someone had to know that this particular collection was at X University and covered a certain subject or period.
And even then, you couldn't count on the fact that the person who wanted to use it would know the types of materials were in that collection.
Now that many of these collections have been cataloged, what we're finding is people are coming upon a particular title that is an interest to them and they want to come and use and work with.
And they have no idea in the world that it was part of the Annex P. Brown military collection or part of a collection that was formed that was an interest in a particular subject.
They may not even be working in that particular subject area.

There's a good deal that libraries are doing now through these digitalization projects that is making materials available on the internet, but not with the idea that that use is going to replace or support the importance of the artifact, but that it will in fact bring people to the library to use those artifacts.
I think the worst thing a library can do in a sense

would be to accept the collection simply because of an iconic value and without any idea of why it fit into that institution, collecting the gold book house, the port of the mission, and simply salt it away on the shelves because it was nice to have.
And that indeed may have gone on in some places in the past, but I don't think it's today's vision of their book librarianship.
